Fragmentation of the Flat World
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman said so. Friedman chose this provocative title for his bestseller to draw attention to the astonishing impact of technology on the global economy.
Distances are shrinking.
Geographical barriers can no longer provide protection easily.
Manufacturing workers in Europe and America and high-tech professionals must face the challenge of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they speak with may well be in India.
Skeptics point out the limitations of Friedman's metaphor.
As one put it, the world is not flat but "uneven."
The contour map of world economic activity shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of scarcity.
Moreover, distances still matter a great deal.
Even neighboring countries with low trade barriers, such as Canada and the United States, engage in much more domestic trade than cross-border trade.
While Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, Vancouver trades far more with Toronto, which is further away, than with nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman made an important point.
Globalization can be defined as interdependence among different continents, with a history as long as that of human civilization, witnessing migrations of races and religions, and the ancient trade routes along the Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different; it is both faster and deeper.
In 1868, when the first transatlantic cable was laid, Europeans and Americans could communicate with each other in just one minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes described a British man in London placing orders for goods from around the world over the telephone and waiting at home to receive them by afternoon.
But Keynes's British man was an exception.
Today, millions upon millions of people all over the globe can purchase goods from around the world at their local supermarkets.
Similarly, 20 years ago, there was instantaneous global communication, but it exceeded the affordability of most people.
Now, almost anyone can walk into a internet cafe and gain the abilities previously held only by governments, multinational corporations, and a few individuals or institutions with large budgets.
A significant reduction in computing, communications, and transportation costs has made technology more accessible.
Just 10 years ago, two-thirds of Internet users were concentrated in the United States.
Today, U.S. Internet users make up less than a quarter of the global total.
Knowledge is power, and today more people possess information than ever before in human history.
Non-state entities now have capabilities once held only by governments.
National states remain the primary actors in world politics for now, but they must learn to share the vast stage with a wider array of participants, including institutions like Oxfam, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like al-Qaeda.
This flattening process is reversible.
This sort of phenomenon has happened before.
The world economy was highly integrated in 1914, but economic interdependence declined sharply over the ensuing thirty years.
It was not until the 1970s that the global economy regained the degree of integration it had reached earlier, even though the Iron Curtain still posed formidable barriers.
The First World War was a trigger for this reversal, and during the interwar period, World War II, and the Cold War, we saw a decline in economic globalization alongside an increase in military globalization.
This reflected deeper issues of domestic inequality resulting from economic development in the nineteenth century.
Politics failed to keep pace with economic developments, resulting in abnormal ideological extremes – fascism and communism – that contributed to the fragmentation of both nations and the world.
Post-World War II Western welfare states provided a safety net for those harmed by economic change, encouraging them to accept the rewards of global economic interdependence.
Some analysts argue that China's role today is similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising powers troubled by domestic inequalities, constantly moving towards nationalism and challenging dominant forces, ultimately leading to world wars that reverse the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the US and China are highly interdependent today, the economies of Britain and Germany before 1914 were similarly intertwined.
But this reasoning is flawed.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had already surpassed that of the UK.
But even with current high growth rates, China's economy is unlikely to catch up with the US within at least two decades.
The bigger threat to the flat world may come from non-state and transnational forces unleashed by technological spread.
On September 11, 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in a surprise attack than the Japanese government did in Pearl Harbor in 1941.
I call this phenomenon privatization of war.
If such forces were to acquire nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would be turned upside down.
Then the movement of people and goods across borders would become much harder.
If these forces were to disrupt the oil exports of the Persian Gulf, which holds two-thirds of the world's proven oil reserves, a global economic recession like the one in the 1930s could further strengthen the power of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two major drivers of globalization.
To date, policies have further reinforced the flattening effects of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken a leadership position in promoting policies that remove barriers.
But the events described above could reverse such policies.
Certain critics of globalization might be willing to see such a result.
But such a result, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst outcomes in two areas—reverse the trend toward economic globalization that spreads technology and power, while cementing the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization, such as war, terror, the spread of climate change, and the spread of pandemics.
If that is the case, the flat world will become a desert.
